We tested our adaptive management in anther application. In this application, a ‚Äúcompute‚Äù component performed certain
amount of computation on a local array. The component was initialized with four processes. Each process was on a SMP. The
component process first checked the local array size. If it was large enough, it would trigger an event. This event would be
captured by the ‚Äúadaptive‚Äù component. It generated an adaptive policy. This policy defined that the compute processes would

468

Yunfeng Peng et al. / Procedia Computer Science 4 (2011) 461‚Äì470

spawn some new processes. And an ‚Äúadaptivef‚Äù method performed the spawn operation, and scattered some data to each new
process. After computation, the data were collected to the original four processes.
Figure 10 gives the test results of the application. From Figure 10, we can see clearly that our load balance mechanism can
improve the performance of parallel components. And Figure 11 gives the test results. The adaptive policy was increase of the
parallel degree. Our adaptive mechanism achieved a much better performance because the computation didn‚Äôt involve much
communication.
We tested our schedule mechanism using a time criterion. We established a composite component. There were some
computing tasks groups in this component. Every task was given a time weight proportional to its execution time on a single
CPU core. The ‚Äúschedule‚Äù component called the ‚Äútaskgq‚Äù method in the ‚Äúschedule‚Äù interface on the composite component. It
then got the tasks groups‚Äô information. It generated a policy based on time criterion. The ‚Äúscheduler‚Äù method in the ‚Äúschedule‚Äù
interface executed the policy.
We tested our ‚Äúperformance‚Äù, ‚Äúrequirement‚Äù, and ‚Äúdeployment‚Äù component together. We built an image processing
application composed of five components. An ‚Äúinit‚Äù component initialized the processing environment. Then a ‚Äúscatter‚Äù
component read some images and sent them to some ‚Äúprocessing‚Äù component processes. The images were median filtered by
these processes. The results were collected by a ‚Äúgather‚Äù component. We added ‚Äúperformance‚Äù, ‚Äúrequirement‚Äù, and
‚Äúdeployment‚Äù interfaces to the ‚Äúscatter‚Äù and the ‚Äúprocessing‚Äù components. For resource requirement, we defined that the
‚Äúscatter‚Äù component needed memory larger than 4G. And the ‚Äúprocessing‚Äù component needed a CPU with a frequency faster
than 2.4GHZ. In our test, the machines satisfied these two conditions were used for the performance prediction of these two
components. And an approximately optimized deployment was generated. The ‚Äúscatter‚Äù component was deployed on a machine
with 8G memory. A ‚Äúprocessing‚Äù component process was deployed on a SMP. The other three components were randomly
deployed. We considered that they didn‚Äôt affect the performance too much. Figure 12 gives the test results of our schedule
mechanism. It was performed on a SMP. Figure 13 shows the test results of our deployment mechanism.

